WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.900 --> 00:00:07.960
- Good afternoon, and welcome
to the Radcliffe Institute

00:00:07.960 --> 00:00:09.280
for Advanced Study.

00:00:09.280 --> 00:00:11.560
My name is Janet Rich-Edwards.

00:00:11.560 --> 00:00:14.120
I am one of the advisors
to the academic Ventures

00:00:14.120 --> 00:00:15.880
Program, which
brings you programs

00:00:15.880 --> 00:00:17.620
like this here at Radcliffe.

00:00:17.620 --> 00:00:20.020
And I also happen to
be an epidemiologist.

00:00:20.020 --> 00:00:22.120
This has been a
banner year for me,

00:00:22.120 --> 00:00:26.980
because we have been able to
put on a series of lectures

00:00:26.980 --> 00:00:28.780
about epidemiology.

00:00:28.780 --> 00:00:31.900
This one, I'm glad you're here,
is the penultimate lecture.

00:00:31.900 --> 00:00:35.830
We have one more on April 23
about Alzheimer's disease.

00:00:35.830 --> 00:00:38.530
But I am absolutely
thrilled to welcome

00:00:38.530 --> 00:00:41.230
the team of Cody Stanford
to give a talk today

00:00:41.230 --> 00:00:44.560
about obesity, which is
arguably one of the greatest

00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:48.040
public health challenges
we face in our lifetime.

00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:50.530
She's an instructor of
medicine and pediatrics

00:00:50.530 --> 00:00:52.270
at Harvard Medical School.

00:00:52.270 --> 00:00:54.610
A leading expert on
obesity, Dr. Stanford

00:00:54.610 --> 00:00:57.730
provides clinical care,
supervises trainees,

00:00:57.730 --> 00:00:59.710
administers a
clinic, and conducts

00:00:59.710 --> 00:01:03.160
research on obesity, health
policy, and health disparities

00:01:03.160 --> 00:01:06.050
to enhance knowledge
and quality of care.

00:01:06.050 --> 00:01:08.260
In addition to teaching in
clinical work at Harvard,

00:01:08.260 --> 00:01:11.800
and in the Massachusetts
MGH Weight Center,

00:01:11.800 --> 00:01:13.810
she conducts clinical
research to evaluate

00:01:13.810 --> 00:01:17.080
the efficacy of weight
loss medications

00:01:17.080 --> 00:01:19.210
as an adjunct to
weight loss surgery,

00:01:19.210 --> 00:01:22.360
delineate the metabolic changes
associated with adolescents who

00:01:22.360 --> 00:01:25.510
undergo weight loss surgery,
and evaluate obesity treatment

00:01:25.510 --> 00:01:27.760
coverage in the United States.

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:31.580
She's been featured in national
news, broadcasts, magazines,

00:01:31.580 --> 00:01:34.510
newspapers, web sites on
issues related to obesity.

00:01:34.510 --> 00:01:38.560
And I just learned that she
won the medical community's

00:01:38.560 --> 00:01:40.930
equivalent of the Oscars.

00:01:40.930 --> 00:01:42.500
It's called the Doxey Award.

00:01:42.500 --> 00:01:44.100
It's a great golden statuette.

00:01:44.100 --> 00:01:46.616
Just, I think, like, last week.

00:01:46.616 --> 00:01:49.460
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:49.460 --> 00:01:53.150
In addition to all that, and
this long string of letters

00:01:53.150 --> 00:01:55.820
you see after her name, she's
a recipient of the Harvard

00:01:55.820 --> 00:01:58.550
Medical School Diversity Award,
and the Massachusetts Medical

00:01:58.550 --> 00:02:00.620
Society's Women's Health Award.

00:02:00.620 --> 00:02:04.220
She received her master's
in public health from Emory,

00:02:04.220 --> 00:02:05.660
her M.D. From the
medical college

00:02:05.660 --> 00:02:07.940
of Georgia School of
Medicine, and her master's

00:02:07.940 --> 00:02:10.310
in public administration
from the Kennedy School.

00:02:10.310 --> 00:02:13.106
Please welcome Dr.
Fatima Cody Stanford.

00:02:13.106 --> 00:02:15.010
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:20.179 --> 00:02:21.220
- Good evening, everyone.

00:02:21.220 --> 00:02:22.360
Can you hear me?

00:02:22.360 --> 00:02:23.410
OK, good evening.

00:02:23.410 --> 00:02:25.600
I'm a walker and a
talker, so you'll

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:28.410
see me walk throughout the
course of this lecture.

00:02:28.410 --> 00:02:30.640
Today, you're here to
learn about obesity.

00:02:30.640 --> 00:02:33.410
And I hope that by the
end of this lecture,

00:02:33.410 --> 00:02:36.580
you'll leave with some new
insights about obesity,

00:02:36.580 --> 00:02:39.670
and its role in our
current structure

00:02:39.670 --> 00:02:43.239
as it relates to health,
and multiple of issues.

00:02:43.239 --> 00:02:45.280
I'm not going to spend
time talking about myself.

00:02:45.280 --> 00:02:47.480
Thank you, Dr. Rich-Edwards.

00:02:47.480 --> 00:02:48.730
So we will pass by that.

00:02:48.730 --> 00:02:51.520
So what are the questions
of interest today?

00:02:51.520 --> 00:02:53.530
What is obesity, and
what is its prevalence

00:02:53.530 --> 00:02:55.930
in the United States,
and throughout the world?

00:02:55.930 --> 00:02:57.650
We'll learn about
the epidemiology.

00:02:57.650 --> 00:03:00.370
So we'll talk about
that initially.

00:03:00.370 --> 00:03:01.930
Is obesity really complex?

00:03:01.930 --> 00:03:03.670
You think it may be not complex.

00:03:03.670 --> 00:03:05.680
Like, we are here to
understand why that is.

00:03:05.680 --> 00:03:09.530
And if it is really complex,
how do we understand it?

00:03:09.530 --> 00:03:11.830
How do we glean information?

00:03:11.830 --> 00:03:14.530
How prevalent is weight
bias, and how do we

00:03:14.530 --> 00:03:16.870
work to change it?

00:03:16.870 --> 00:03:18.550
And what are some
clinical interventions

00:03:18.550 --> 00:03:20.600
for the treatment of obesity?

00:03:20.600 --> 00:03:22.360
Now I'm going to step
on a soapbox moment

00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:23.901
at the very beginning
of this lecture

00:03:23.901 --> 00:03:27.190
to talk about our language
regarding obesity here

00:03:27.190 --> 00:03:28.780
in the United States.

00:03:28.780 --> 00:03:31.360
Often, we will refer to
patients as obese patient.

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:34.090
We use words such as
morbid obesity, fat.

00:03:34.090 --> 00:03:35.800
I want us to change
that thinking

00:03:35.800 --> 00:03:39.190
because that thinking, our
language in and of itself,

00:03:39.190 --> 00:03:41.600
promotes weight bias and stigma.

00:03:41.600 --> 00:03:44.020
So this is a disease
process like any other.

00:03:44.020 --> 00:03:47.560
We talk about these as
patients with obesity,

00:03:47.560 --> 00:03:50.260
patients with severe obesity.

00:03:50.260 --> 00:03:53.410
We take out the term morbid,
because we don't utilize it

00:03:53.410 --> 00:03:57.520
for any other disease process
i.e. cancer, heart disease,

00:03:57.520 --> 00:03:59.620
things that could
potentially kill patients.

00:03:59.620 --> 00:04:01.090
And so let's remove that.

00:04:01.090 --> 00:04:03.137
You'll hear me talk with
people first, language,

00:04:03.137 --> 00:04:04.720
throughout the course
of this lecture,

00:04:04.720 --> 00:04:08.410
and I challenge you to do
the same in your daily life.

00:04:08.410 --> 00:04:11.040
Now let's look at obesity
and its prevalence

00:04:11.040 --> 00:04:13.300
compared to other
disease processes.

00:04:13.300 --> 00:04:16.540
We'll start with commonly
discussed disease processes.

00:04:16.540 --> 00:04:19.220
HIV at the bottom of this list.

00:04:19.220 --> 00:04:20.829
We have 1.2 million people.

00:04:20.829 --> 00:04:23.590
We have colon cancer
here with 1.2 million.

00:04:23.590 --> 00:04:26.680
Breast cancer gets a lot
of attention, 2.8 million.

00:04:26.680 --> 00:04:29.890
All cancers combined,
13.8 million.

00:04:29.890 --> 00:04:32.500
Diabetes 37.2 million.

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:35.440
NAFLD is nonalcoholic
fatty liver disease.

00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:37.420
You can see 80.3 million.

00:04:37.420 --> 00:04:40.850
And then obesity, 93.4 million.

00:04:40.850 --> 00:04:43.390
Let's go look at how many people
own a TV here in the United

00:04:43.390 --> 00:04:43.889
States.

00:04:43.889 --> 00:04:45.670
115.6 million.

00:04:45.670 --> 00:04:47.000
People that own a smartphone.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:48.875
We spend a lot more time
on our smartphones--

00:04:48.875 --> 00:04:50.480
205.4 million.

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:54.730
So what you can see here is
that 93 million adults struggle

00:04:54.730 --> 00:04:56.980
with obesity.

00:04:56.980 --> 00:05:02.660
Approximately 40% of the US
adult population has obesity.

00:05:02.660 --> 00:05:04.700
But why are we not
doing much about it?

00:05:04.700 --> 00:05:07.460
I think a lot of that has to do
with our lack of understanding,

00:05:07.460 --> 00:05:12.140
and a lot of are placing blame
on patients, which we can hope

00:05:12.140 --> 00:05:14.750
to change after this lecture.

00:05:14.750 --> 00:05:17.300
Now when we look at
obesity, often, we

00:05:17.300 --> 00:05:20.090
will look at it in terms of the
BMI, or the body mass index.

00:05:20.090 --> 00:05:22.790
It determines height and
weight, and then gives us

00:05:22.790 --> 00:05:25.100
a kind of a measure,
crude measure,

00:05:25.100 --> 00:05:27.740
to help determine
who has obesity.

00:05:27.740 --> 00:05:30.440
We'll look at the guidelines
for children and adults

00:05:30.440 --> 00:05:31.979
that have obesity.

00:05:31.979 --> 00:05:33.270
There are different guidelines.

00:05:33.270 --> 00:05:35.960
So if you're thinking about
your child or grandchild,

00:05:35.960 --> 00:05:38.970
I want you to realize that
there are different criteria.

00:05:38.970 --> 00:05:42.186
We'll start looking at
the pediatric population.

00:05:42.186 --> 00:05:44.435
So how is obesity defined
in children and adolescents.

00:05:44.435 --> 00:05:47.870
It's done based upon growth
measurements taken from the age

00:05:47.870 --> 00:05:50.420
of 2 up until the age of 20.

00:05:50.420 --> 00:05:52.520
So those that are
underweight have less

00:05:52.520 --> 00:05:54.060
than the fifth percentile.

00:05:54.060 --> 00:05:56.060
Those that are considered
to be a healthy weight

00:05:56.060 --> 00:05:59.210
between the fifth and less
than the 85th percentiles.

00:05:59.210 --> 00:06:00.890
Those that are
considered overweight,

00:06:00.890 --> 00:06:03.950
between the 85th and less
than the 95th percentile.

00:06:03.950 --> 00:06:06.410
And those that have
obesity greater

00:06:06.410 --> 00:06:08.730
than or equal to
the 95th percentile.

00:06:08.730 --> 00:06:11.450
Now there are criteria that
go beyond this, meaning

00:06:11.450 --> 00:06:13.010
as we get into severe obesity.

00:06:13.010 --> 00:06:16.400
I'm not going to specifically
focus on that here with regard

00:06:16.400 --> 00:06:18.960
to the children and
adolescent population.

00:06:18.960 --> 00:06:21.202
However, I won't
do that for adults.

00:06:21.202 --> 00:06:22.910
Now when we look at
adults, because we've

00:06:22.910 --> 00:06:25.190
stopped growing
vertically, we actually

00:06:25.190 --> 00:06:28.515
have just a BMI criteria
that defines adults.

00:06:28.515 --> 00:06:30.890
And this is utilized, not only
here in the United States,

00:06:30.890 --> 00:06:32.510
but by the World
Health Organization

00:06:32.510 --> 00:06:34.455
throughout the world.

00:06:34.455 --> 00:06:36.830
So when we look at those that
are considered underweight,

00:06:36.830 --> 00:06:39.670
they have a BMI
of less than 18.5.

00:06:39.670 --> 00:06:41.045
And for those that
are considered

00:06:41.045 --> 00:06:45.590
of normal or healthy weight,
a BMI from 18.5 to 24.9,

00:06:45.590 --> 00:06:47.120
we start to get
into overweight when

00:06:47.120 --> 00:06:50.210
we get to BMIs from 25 to 29.9.

00:06:50.210 --> 00:06:51.854
And then we get into obesity.

00:06:51.854 --> 00:06:53.270
And what you can
see on the screen

00:06:53.270 --> 00:06:56.900
is we have class 1, class
2, and class 3 obesity--

00:06:56.900 --> 00:06:59.540
mild, moderate,
and severe obesity.

00:06:59.540 --> 00:07:03.260
Mild obesity being classified
as a BMI of 30 to 34.9.

00:07:03.260 --> 00:07:08.390
Class 2 obesity classified
as a BMI of 35 to 39.9.

00:07:08.390 --> 00:07:11.270
And then those that
have BMI and excess

00:07:11.270 --> 00:07:16.980
or equal to 40 being categorized
as having severe obesity.

00:07:16.980 --> 00:07:19.310
Now what I'm going to do is
just take you very briefly

00:07:19.310 --> 00:07:21.590
through some of
the epidemiology,

00:07:21.590 --> 00:07:23.630
starting very recently, 2011.

00:07:23.630 --> 00:07:26.510
Often, when I use the slides,
I'll start back from 1980,

00:07:26.510 --> 00:07:28.100
and bring us up to now.

00:07:28.100 --> 00:07:30.170
But we all know that
obesity rates are climbing,

00:07:30.170 --> 00:07:31.350
that's part of why you're here.

00:07:31.350 --> 00:07:33.600
So I didn't want to really
kind of belabor that point.

00:07:33.600 --> 00:07:36.050
But I do want to point
out some nuances here.

00:07:36.050 --> 00:07:40.550
So if you look at this graphic
here of the United States,

00:07:40.550 --> 00:07:44.900
this is looking at obesity
amongst US adults by state.

00:07:44.900 --> 00:07:47.240
I want to point out kind
of some key things in terms

00:07:47.240 --> 00:07:50.090
of the coloring
here on the graph.

00:07:50.090 --> 00:07:53.390
States that have less than
20% obesity rates, if you

00:07:53.390 --> 00:07:56.300
can find one, let me know
about it, but no one does.

00:07:56.300 --> 00:07:59.090
Colorado was the
last to hang onto it.

00:07:59.090 --> 00:08:01.670
20% to 25% in green--

00:08:01.670 --> 00:08:03.920
so this is the percent
of the population.

00:08:03.920 --> 00:08:07.072
In yellow, 25% to less than 30%.

00:08:07.072 --> 00:08:08.780
In the orange, which
is just concentrated

00:08:08.780 --> 00:08:12.050
a lot here in the southeast
and in the Midwest, 30%

00:08:12.050 --> 00:08:13.550
to less than 35%.

00:08:13.550 --> 00:08:17.360
And then greater than or
equal to 35% obesity rates.

00:08:17.360 --> 00:08:19.682
Now I want to give you a
little bit more information--

00:08:19.682 --> 00:08:21.140
and this is for
the epidemiologists

00:08:21.140 --> 00:08:23.348
in the room-- this is from
the Behavioral Risk Factor

00:08:23.348 --> 00:08:26.480
Surveillance System,
which is self-report data.

00:08:26.480 --> 00:08:31.640
And so that means that this
is probably not even accurate.

00:08:31.640 --> 00:08:34.640
I just want you to think back to
your driver's license, and what

00:08:34.640 --> 00:08:37.309
weight you put on there, and
what weight you actually are,

00:08:37.309 --> 00:08:39.200
and you tell me
if those coincide.

00:08:39.200 --> 00:08:41.720
Now if they coincide, and
you're actually accurate,

00:08:41.720 --> 00:08:42.330
that's great.

00:08:42.330 --> 00:08:45.140
But most people, fudge
the things a little bit.

00:08:45.140 --> 00:08:48.050
So what you can see
here-- this was 2011.

00:08:48.050 --> 00:08:50.540
Now in 2012, we
see a pretty shift.

00:08:50.540 --> 00:08:52.580
You're like, wow, in
one year we shifted?

00:08:52.580 --> 00:08:54.230
2013.

00:08:54.230 --> 00:08:55.760
2014.

00:08:55.760 --> 00:08:57.350
2015.

00:08:57.350 --> 00:08:58.040
OK?

00:08:58.040 --> 00:09:00.110
So we see a change,
and you guys you

00:09:00.110 --> 00:09:02.570
would agree with me that
there is a bit more orange.

00:09:02.570 --> 00:09:04.836
Some red has kind have
crept into the area.

00:09:04.836 --> 00:09:06.710
We start seeing some of
the southern states--

00:09:06.710 --> 00:09:09.770
Mississippi, Alabama, Louisiana,
and then West Virginia

00:09:09.770 --> 00:09:12.290
getting obesity rates
by self-report data

00:09:12.290 --> 00:09:14.840
in excess of 35%.

00:09:14.840 --> 00:09:16.760
We see Guam here
on the outlying,

00:09:16.760 --> 00:09:18.300
and we see some differences.

00:09:18.300 --> 00:09:20.510
So of course, everyone's
looking up to Massachusetts.

00:09:20.510 --> 00:09:23.840
And we like to tout ourselves
on the back-- we're 20% to 25%.

00:09:23.840 --> 00:09:24.920
But really?

00:09:24.920 --> 00:09:29.000
Still 20% to 25% of the
population with obesity

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:30.230
by self-report?

00:09:30.230 --> 00:09:32.760
I mean, do we really need to
pat ourselves on the back?

00:09:32.760 --> 00:09:34.997
I don't know if we
should really get a pass.

00:09:34.997 --> 00:09:36.830
Now what I'm going to
do is I'm like to look

00:09:36.830 --> 00:09:39.830
at this by race and
ethnicity-- by the three

00:09:39.830 --> 00:09:42.180
major racial ethnic groups
here in the United States.

00:09:42.180 --> 00:09:44.180
We'll start looking
at white adults,

00:09:44.180 --> 00:09:45.890
we'll go into looking
at Hispanic adults,

00:09:45.890 --> 00:09:47.556
and we'll finish
looking at black adults

00:09:47.556 --> 00:09:49.600
here in the United States
by self-report data--

00:09:49.600 --> 00:09:50.870
remember that.

00:09:50.870 --> 00:09:55.310
So if we look here, you can see
that there is some distribution

00:09:55.310 --> 00:09:59.350
of obesity in West Virginia.

00:09:59.350 --> 00:10:01.120
And we have Puerto Rico here.

00:10:01.120 --> 00:10:04.060
For those that are white adults
here in the United States,

00:10:04.060 --> 00:10:06.250
Colorado does have
that less than 20%,

00:10:06.250 --> 00:10:08.620
specifically for white adults.

00:10:08.620 --> 00:10:12.550
DC, so the District of
Columbia, and Hawaii.

00:10:12.550 --> 00:10:14.380
I wanted to say Hawaii.

00:10:14.380 --> 00:10:15.820
So less than 20%.

00:10:15.820 --> 00:10:16.870
OK?

00:10:16.870 --> 00:10:19.420
Let's look at what happens
when we look at Hispanic adults

00:10:19.420 --> 00:10:21.040
here in the United States.

00:10:21.040 --> 00:10:23.710
We do see an oranging,
a reddening of the map.

00:10:23.710 --> 00:10:25.360
Would you guys agree with that?

00:10:25.360 --> 00:10:28.600
So we start seeing a
lot more red distributed

00:10:28.600 --> 00:10:31.270
throughout the United States.

00:10:31.270 --> 00:10:33.880
I think that the graphic
that's most concerning

00:10:33.880 --> 00:10:37.040
is this last one, which is
black adults here in the United

00:10:37.040 --> 00:10:37.540
States.

00:10:37.540 --> 00:10:39.580
This is a lot of what
brought me to this work.

00:10:39.580 --> 00:10:41.413
I mean, you guys probably
recognize that I'm

00:10:41.413 --> 00:10:42.800
an African-American woman.

00:10:42.800 --> 00:10:45.610
And so I was always
concerned at why was there

00:10:45.610 --> 00:10:46.780
such a huge disparity.

00:10:46.780 --> 00:10:50.920
You can see that most of
this map is red in nature.

00:10:50.920 --> 00:10:53.590
And while red is a lovely
color, in this situation,

00:10:53.590 --> 00:10:56.470
it's not one that precludes
positive thoughts.

00:10:56.470 --> 00:10:58.180
And so part of my
work on disparities

00:10:58.180 --> 00:11:00.400
is really to address
and understand

00:11:00.400 --> 00:11:03.220
why there's such a difference
in the prevalence of obesity

00:11:03.220 --> 00:11:06.400
by race and ethnicity
here in the United States.

00:11:06.400 --> 00:11:08.050
Now a lot of people
often say to me

00:11:08.050 --> 00:11:10.270
that this is just a US problem.

00:11:10.270 --> 00:11:12.290
When I go other places
around the world,

00:11:12.290 --> 00:11:13.540
I don't really notice obesity.

00:11:13.540 --> 00:11:15.880
And I would challenge your
thinking on this notion.

00:11:15.880 --> 00:11:20.200
Greater than 10% of the
world's population has obesity.

00:11:20.200 --> 00:11:22.729
So that means it is
pandemic in nature.

00:11:22.729 --> 00:11:25.270
And I want to focus on some of
the areas that might have been

00:11:25.270 --> 00:11:26.240
a little bit shocking to you.

00:11:26.240 --> 00:11:27.850
Obviously, we have
the United States.

00:11:27.850 --> 00:11:29.410
We have Alaska.

