00:17:42.140 --> 00:17:45.160
the signaling to
change such that we

00:17:45.160 --> 00:17:48.130
can have an impact on
someone's likelihood

00:17:48.130 --> 00:17:50.770
to go down this
preferential pathway as it

00:17:50.770 --> 00:17:53.260
relates to weight regulation.

00:17:53.260 --> 00:17:54.580
So let's look at BDNF.

00:17:54.580 --> 00:17:57.460
We talked about brain derived
neurotropic factor regulation

00:17:57.460 --> 00:18:00.311
and obesity, talking
about the role it plays.

00:18:00.311 --> 00:18:01.810
And so what they
did was they looked

00:18:01.810 --> 00:18:05.560
at about 30,000 individuals,
and they tried to determine,

00:18:05.560 --> 00:18:06.405
what's going on.

00:18:06.405 --> 00:18:08.530
What are we seeing, and
how does that differ, maybe

00:18:08.530 --> 00:18:10.360
by race and ethnicity?

00:18:10.360 --> 00:18:13.900
What they found were
that people with obesity

00:18:13.900 --> 00:18:17.890
had a CC pair of this
heterogeneous nucleotide,

00:18:17.890 --> 00:18:19.630
ribonuclear protein D0B--

00:18:19.630 --> 00:18:21.740
I'll ask you guys
about that later--

00:18:21.740 --> 00:18:23.720
CC pair.

00:18:23.720 --> 00:18:26.380
And for those people
that have this pair,

00:18:26.380 --> 00:18:29.500
they have low levels of brain
derived neurotrophic factor,

00:18:29.500 --> 00:18:32.140
and higher levels of obesity.

00:18:32.140 --> 00:18:35.620
Those that had a TT
pair had high levels

00:18:35.620 --> 00:18:37.420
of brain derived
neurotrophic factor,

00:18:37.420 --> 00:18:39.490
and tended to have lean figures.

00:18:39.490 --> 00:18:43.700
And those that had a TC pair--
kind of fill in the middle--

00:18:43.700 --> 00:18:46.640
they had medium likelihood
of having obesity.

00:18:46.640 --> 00:18:48.910
Now when they looked at
this by race and ethnicity,

00:18:48.910 --> 00:18:50.530
Hispanic and
African-Americans were

00:18:50.530 --> 00:18:54.310
more likely to have either
a CC pair or a CT pair

00:18:54.310 --> 00:18:55.910
compared to white individuals.

00:18:55.910 --> 00:18:58.060
And so maybe this
is one factor that

00:18:58.060 --> 00:19:02.410
plays a role in the
difference in obesity rates

00:19:02.410 --> 00:19:04.880
here in the United States.

00:19:04.880 --> 00:19:06.790
Now I'm going to switch
gears a little bit

00:19:06.790 --> 00:19:09.400
and talk about the concept
of fetal programming,

00:19:09.400 --> 00:19:14.410
and what does fetal programming
mean as it relates to obesity.

00:19:14.410 --> 00:19:15.920
And why is it important?

00:19:15.920 --> 00:19:19.750
Why do I think it is probably
one of the untapped mechanisms

00:19:19.750 --> 00:19:22.480
of controlling obesity,
not only in the US,

00:19:22.480 --> 00:19:24.040
but around the world?

00:19:24.040 --> 00:19:27.640
So if a mom goes into pregnancy
with overweight or obesity,

00:19:27.640 --> 00:19:31.520
she has increased inflammation,
increased insulin resistance,

00:19:31.520 --> 00:19:35.110
breakdown of cholesterol, and
she has inflammatory markers

00:19:35.110 --> 00:19:36.640
that are elevated.

00:19:36.640 --> 00:19:38.980
That then exposes
the fetus to lipids.

00:19:38.980 --> 00:19:40.710
Lipids are kind of cholesterol.

00:19:40.710 --> 00:19:43.540
And it reprograms
their gene targets such

00:19:43.540 --> 00:19:46.315
that they not only have an
increased amount of lipids

00:19:46.315 --> 00:19:48.250
or cholesterol in
their liver, they're

00:19:48.250 --> 00:19:50.740
also struggling with issues
in their skeletal muscle,

00:19:50.740 --> 00:19:53.350
their adipose, which is
fat tissue, their brain,

00:19:53.350 --> 00:19:54.700
and their pancreas.

00:19:54.700 --> 00:19:57.310
Then that leads to risk
of childhood disease.

00:19:57.310 --> 00:20:00.190
That NAFLD, that nonalcoholic
fatty liver disease

00:20:00.190 --> 00:20:01.840
that we talked about earlier.

00:20:01.840 --> 00:20:05.180
Insulin resistance,
obesity, hyperphasia,

00:20:05.180 --> 00:20:08.560
which means that I have an
insatiable desire to eat,

00:20:08.560 --> 00:20:09.811
and diabetes.

00:20:09.811 --> 00:20:11.560
So I just told you
that I think that there

00:20:11.560 --> 00:20:16.330
is an untapped strategy
of really targeting moms

00:20:16.330 --> 00:20:18.632
prior to conception,
and let's look at why.

00:20:18.632 --> 00:20:20.840
We're going to look at a
study that's been conducted.

00:20:20.840 --> 00:20:23.470
This is a prospective
study, so going forward,

00:20:23.470 --> 00:20:25.619
about 20 years of
duration at this time,

00:20:25.619 --> 00:20:27.160
and it's looking at
children that are

00:20:27.160 --> 00:20:30.190
born to the same mom and dad.

00:20:30.190 --> 00:20:33.110
One born before the mom
had weight loss surgery,

00:20:33.110 --> 00:20:36.390
The second born after the
mom had weight loss surgery.

00:20:36.390 --> 00:20:40.030
So same genetic makeup,
same mom and dad,

00:20:40.030 --> 00:20:43.070
but different levels of obesity.

00:20:43.070 --> 00:20:46.680
So BMS stands for
before maternal surgery.

00:20:46.680 --> 00:20:48.520
AMS stands for after
maternal surgery.

00:20:48.520 --> 00:20:52.370
And that surgery specifically
is weight loss surgery.

00:20:52.370 --> 00:20:55.220
So we're going to compare
these two columns.

00:20:55.220 --> 00:20:58.240
So obviously here,
there's similar numbers

00:20:58.240 --> 00:20:59.640
of males and females.

00:20:59.640 --> 00:21:01.390
You can see that the
birth weight of those

00:21:01.390 --> 00:21:03.940
born to the children that
were born before the mom had

00:21:03.940 --> 00:21:06.820
surgery, which means that
she had severe obesity,

00:21:06.820 --> 00:21:08.380
is different.

00:21:08.380 --> 00:21:11.240
Macrosomia means
children with a big body.

00:21:11.240 --> 00:21:13.660
So those that have
macrosomia, we

00:21:13.660 --> 00:21:16.857
can see much higher prevalence
in those born before surgery.

00:21:16.857 --> 00:21:18.940
There's also going to be
an age difference, right?

00:21:18.940 --> 00:21:21.820
So we expect these to be
older because they were born

00:21:21.820 --> 00:21:22.960
before the mom had surgery.

00:21:22.960 --> 00:21:24.340
The mom had surgery.

00:21:24.340 --> 00:21:26.320
We recommend not getting
pregnant for at least

00:21:26.320 --> 00:21:28.840
the first year, sometimes
two years post-surgery.

00:21:28.840 --> 00:21:30.430
So they're going to be younger.

00:21:30.430 --> 00:21:33.820
The body mass index
percentile lower here.

00:21:33.820 --> 00:21:35.110
Weight, lower.

00:21:35.110 --> 00:21:36.820
Body fat, lower.

00:21:36.820 --> 00:21:38.320
Insulin levels, lower.

00:21:38.320 --> 00:21:40.150
Glucose levels, lower.

00:21:40.150 --> 00:21:44.260
Same mom and dad, child
born after surgery.

00:21:44.260 --> 00:21:46.780
So when we look at children
born after maternal surgery

00:21:46.780 --> 00:21:48.910
versus those born
before surgery,

00:21:48.910 --> 00:21:51.250
there is a threefold
decrease in the prevalence

00:21:51.250 --> 00:21:53.620
of severe obesity
in the children

00:21:53.620 --> 00:21:57.440
that are born after maternal
surgery versus those before.

00:21:57.440 --> 00:21:59.130
There's improved
insulin sensitivity.

00:21:59.130 --> 00:22:02.230
We talked about insulin in
the body being anorexigenic,

00:22:02.230 --> 00:22:04.640
promoting satiety.

00:22:04.640 --> 00:22:07.930
There's improved lipid profile,
improved cholesterol profile.

00:22:07.930 --> 00:22:11.650
We have a decrease in
inflammatory markers like CRP.

00:22:11.650 --> 00:22:12.580
Decrease in leptin.

00:22:12.580 --> 00:22:14.290
increased ghrelin.

00:22:14.290 --> 00:22:17.710
And so what we see across the
board for these individuals

00:22:17.710 --> 00:22:20.050
is that the metabolic
profile has changed just

00:22:20.050 --> 00:22:22.000
by modifying the mother.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:25.080
And by modifying the mother,
we have modified her entry

00:22:25.080 --> 00:22:26.350
into her environment.

00:22:26.350 --> 00:22:28.690
And then the long
term consequences

00:22:28.690 --> 00:22:31.210
of obesity within
the population.

00:22:31.210 --> 00:22:33.779
So I told you I would bring it
back down from the PhD level.

00:22:33.779 --> 00:22:35.320
We're talking about
the brain, right?

00:22:35.320 --> 00:22:38.530
The brain is playing a role in
weight and weight regulation,

00:22:38.530 --> 00:22:40.930
but it does get inputs
from things that we do.

00:22:40.930 --> 00:22:44.470
So diet quality is important.

00:22:44.470 --> 00:22:46.690
I ask patients about
what they're eating,

00:22:46.690 --> 00:22:49.810
not the caloric value
of what they're eating.

00:22:49.810 --> 00:22:53.290
The brain cares more about
the quality of the calories

00:22:53.290 --> 00:22:55.870
than it does about the
number of the calories.

00:22:55.870 --> 00:22:59.040
So if your diet looks like
