So if it looks more like this.

00:23:00.480 --> 00:23:03.280
Now physical activity is
one of my favorite things.

00:23:03.280 --> 00:23:05.200
Many of my lovely
gym members are here

00:23:05.200 --> 00:23:07.204
in this audience today.

00:23:07.204 --> 00:23:08.620
We spent a lot of
time at the gym.

00:23:08.620 --> 00:23:10.040
I think we like to come
and see each other,

00:23:10.040 --> 00:23:12.430
but we also like to work
out pretty aggressively.

00:23:12.430 --> 00:23:14.140
But I want us to
think about what

00:23:14.140 --> 00:23:18.460
role physical activity actually
plays in weight regulation.

00:23:18.460 --> 00:23:19.990
And what I want to
tell you guys is

00:23:19.990 --> 00:23:22.780
that on average, people
that are physically active

00:23:22.780 --> 00:23:24.670
maintain their weight.

00:23:24.670 --> 00:23:27.100
But at the beginning of the
year, every single year,

00:23:27.100 --> 00:23:30.840
people go and join the
gym to do what, you guys?

00:23:30.840 --> 00:23:31.830
Lose weight, right?

00:23:31.830 --> 00:23:34.180
And so after two months
of them going to the gym,

00:23:34.180 --> 00:23:36.840
and they don't lose
weight, what happens?

00:23:36.840 --> 00:23:38.815
They stop going
to the gym, right?

00:23:38.815 --> 00:23:40.440
They stop going to
the gym because they

00:23:40.440 --> 00:23:41.231
didn't lose weight.

00:23:41.231 --> 00:23:43.500
One of the questions that
I always ask my patients

00:23:43.500 --> 00:23:45.840
is, did you gain weight?

00:23:45.840 --> 00:23:48.670
And often, they say no, but
they went to lose weight.

00:23:48.670 --> 00:23:51.540
And so since that was not
what they accomplished,

00:23:51.540 --> 00:23:52.860
they stopped going to the gym.

00:23:52.860 --> 00:23:56.880
My thinking is that we
need to change what's

00:23:56.880 --> 00:23:58.530
being stated about
physical activity,

00:23:58.530 --> 00:24:00.930
because we know in
big meta analyzes

00:24:00.930 --> 00:24:02.790
that the role that
physical activity plays

00:24:02.790 --> 00:24:05.610
is to help with
weight maintenance,

00:24:05.610 --> 00:24:07.620
not to drive significant loss.

00:24:07.620 --> 00:24:10.050
Sleep quality and duration
plays a large role.

00:24:10.050 --> 00:24:13.997
Now this is something I do
not model well for patients.

00:24:13.997 --> 00:24:16.080
For people that know me,
they don't think I sleep.

00:24:16.080 --> 00:24:17.100
I do sleep--

00:24:17.100 --> 00:24:19.560
I just require a lot
less than most people.

00:24:19.560 --> 00:24:21.300
Not one of my stronger suits.

00:24:21.300 --> 00:24:23.850
I can model these other
things pretty well.

00:24:23.850 --> 00:24:27.330
Now medications that we as
physicians provide to patients

00:24:27.330 --> 00:24:28.955
can lead to significant
weight change--

00:24:28.955 --> 00:24:30.746
and I'll spend a little
bit of time talking

00:24:30.746 --> 00:24:32.250
about that in a few minutes.

00:24:32.250 --> 00:24:34.360
Circadian rhythm disturbances.

00:24:34.360 --> 00:24:38.040
So when we go from being a shift
worker to a night shift worker,

00:24:38.040 --> 00:24:40.290
that affects the pathways
that we've already talked

00:24:40.290 --> 00:24:42.000
about that regulate weight.

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:45.150
And just by making that
shift or transition,

00:24:45.150 --> 00:24:47.820
we see significant
shifts in weight,

00:24:47.820 --> 00:24:50.760
as studied by the
Nurses' Health Study.

00:24:50.760 --> 00:24:52.700
And then finally, thermogenesis.

00:24:52.700 --> 00:24:55.350
Thermogenesis is how
much we're burning

00:24:55.350 --> 00:24:56.670
at rest and with activity.

00:24:56.670 --> 00:24:58.600
And a lot of that's
genetic in nature.

00:24:58.600 --> 00:25:00.720
So we can't shift
that significantly.

00:25:00.720 --> 00:25:04.410
So all of these play a role in
how the body regulates weight.

00:25:04.410 --> 00:25:06.570
Now this is one of
my favorite slides.

00:25:06.570 --> 00:25:09.580
I only use it in almost
every single presentation.

00:25:09.580 --> 00:25:11.640
And these are all
of the contributors

00:25:11.640 --> 00:25:14.760
to obesity that we know
of as of right now.

00:25:14.760 --> 00:25:17.340
Now you guys remember
the kind of skills

00:25:17.340 --> 00:25:19.330
that I showed you, like
looking at calories in,

00:25:19.330 --> 00:25:21.630
calories out-- the reason
why that was inaccurate

00:25:21.630 --> 00:25:24.150
is because it didn't take
into account all the factors

00:25:24.150 --> 00:25:26.645
that you see on this slide.

00:25:26.645 --> 00:25:28.770
So what you see here are
that there are things that

00:25:28.770 --> 00:25:31.760
happen inside of an individual.

00:25:31.760 --> 00:25:35.150
There are things that happen
exterior to an individual.

00:25:35.150 --> 00:25:39.010
Things here at the top
increase how much you take in.

00:25:39.010 --> 00:25:40.690
These things here at
the bottom decrease

00:25:40.690 --> 00:25:42.280
how much you're able to burn.

00:25:42.280 --> 00:25:44.380
And these things
here in the middle

00:25:44.380 --> 00:25:47.702
affect either what you take
in, or how much you burn,

00:25:47.702 --> 00:25:49.660
or what you might be able
to see here, it says,

00:25:49.660 --> 00:25:51.790
unknown, or we just
haven't figured it out.

00:25:51.790 --> 00:25:55.960
Now these are all contributors
or influencers to obesity.

00:25:55.960 --> 00:25:58.412
And these colors
actually mean something.

00:25:58.412 --> 00:25:59.870
So these things
here in the purple,

00:25:59.870 --> 00:26:03.500
these are environmental
pressures on physical activity.

00:26:03.500 --> 00:26:04.930
These things here
in the lavender

00:26:04.930 --> 00:26:06.846
that you see kind of
scattered throughout more

00:26:06.846 --> 00:26:10.240
inside of the individual are
biological or medical reasons

00:26:10.240 --> 00:26:12.790
why someone may have obesity.

00:26:12.790 --> 00:26:15.820
Here in the yellow, maternal
or developmental reasons

00:26:15.820 --> 00:26:18.460
why someone may
struggle with obesity.

00:26:18.460 --> 00:26:20.620
The only things we
ever hear about, not

00:26:20.620 --> 00:26:23.369
only in the lay population,
but also in medicine,

00:26:23.369 --> 00:26:25.660
are these things that are
here in the pink and orange--

00:26:25.660 --> 00:26:30.050
economic reasons why someone
may struggle with weight.

00:26:30.050 --> 00:26:34.340
In orange, food and beverage
behaviors, and environments.

00:26:34.340 --> 00:26:36.270
Here in this kind
of green color,

00:26:36.270 --> 00:26:38.570
these are psychological
reasons that might

00:26:38.570 --> 00:26:40.670
be associated with weight.

00:26:40.670 --> 00:26:43.340
And then here in the blue,
we have social reasons.

00:26:43.340 --> 00:26:44.360
OK?

00:26:44.360 --> 00:26:47.634
So these are the contributors
and influencers to obesity.

00:26:47.634 --> 00:26:49.550
I'm not going to go
through each one of those.

00:26:49.550 --> 00:26:51.258
I'll give you guys
the reference for that

00:26:51.258 --> 00:26:53.280
later if you so desire.

00:26:53.280 --> 00:26:56.480
But these are contributors to
obesity inside of the person.

00:26:56.480 --> 00:26:59.060
You can see things that might
affect increasing intake.

00:26:59.060 --> 00:27:02.570
Might be hyper reactivity
to environmental food cues.

00:27:02.570 --> 00:27:05.750
Delayed satiety, so it takes
a longer time to feel full.

00:27:05.750 --> 00:27:07.890
Or disordered eating.

00:27:07.890 --> 00:27:09.770
So if we are restricting
binging, purging,

00:27:09.770 --> 00:27:10.880
things of that sort.

00:27:10.880 --> 00:27:13.070
Decreased expenditure
may be associated

00:27:13.070 --> 00:27:14.572
with a gut microbiota.

00:27:14.572 --> 00:27:16.280
You're like, what does
the gut microbiota

00:27:16.280 --> 00:27:17.450
have to do with this?

00:27:17.450 --> 00:27:19.340
When we look at the
gut microbiota, which

00:27:19.340 --> 00:27:22.550
is the bacteria in the gut
of individuals that are lean

00:27:22.550 --> 00:27:24.170
versus those that
have obesity, we

00:27:24.170 --> 00:27:27.080
see different bacteria
housed in the gut.

00:27:27.080 --> 00:27:30.320
We see a shift in the bacteria
after weight loss surgery.

00:27:30.320 --> 00:27:33.110
And we also often see a
shift if someone gets what's

00:27:33.110 --> 00:27:34.980
called a fecal transplant.

00:27:34.980 --> 00:27:38.480
So if they're getting feces
from an individual for treatment

00:27:38.480 --> 00:27:42.137
of something like C. Diff,
which is Clostridium difficile.

00:27:42.137 --> 00:27:43.970
We can see people lose
weight without making

00:27:43.970 --> 00:27:45.440
any significant
changes if they're

00:27:45.440 --> 00:27:48.796
getting the bacteria of the
gut of a lean individual.

00:27:48.796 --> 00:27:50.420
The alternate is also
true-- if they're

00:27:50.420 --> 00:27:52.580
getting the bacteria of
someone that has obesity,

00:27:52.580 --> 00:27:54.110
they may gain weight.

00:27:54.110 --> 00:27:56.570
So thermogenesis, how
the body's burned.

00:27:56.570 --> 00:28:00.020
Physical disabilities
might affect expenditure.

00:28:00.020 --> 00:28:01.730
Increase intake and
decreased expenditure

00:28:01.730 --> 00:28:04.640
may be secondary to genetic
and epigenetic factors.

00:28:04.640 --> 00:28:05.710
Age related changes.

00:28:05.710 --> 00:28:09.230
Menopause-- huge
in causing changes

00:28:09.230 --> 00:28:11.570
and how weight is distributed.

00:28:11.570 --> 00:28:13.850
I do whole hour long
lectures on that,

00:28:13.850 --> 00:28:15.140
so we won't talk about that.

00:28:15.140 --> 00:28:19.520
Mood disturbances can also
affect intake and expenditure.

00:28:19.520 --> 00:28:21.320
Those things outside
of the person.

00:28:21.320 --> 00:28:23.390
Environmental or
chemical toxins.

00:28:23.390 --> 00:28:25.250
Pervasive food advertising.

00:28:25.250 --> 00:28:27.140
Large portion sizes.

00:28:27.140 --> 00:28:28.910
The built environment,
sedentary time,

00:28:28.910 --> 00:28:31.757
and labor saving devices
might decrease expenditure.

00:28:31.757 --> 00:28:34.340
And things that might increase
intake and decrease expenditure

00:28:34.340 --> 00:28:36.890
may be things like
stress, or weight cycling.

00:28:36.890 --> 00:28:38.510
What people don't
realize is that when

00:28:38.510 --> 00:28:41.750
they restrict their eating,
the body recognize what

00:28:41.750 --> 00:28:43.430
it's baseline or set point is.

00:28:43.430 --> 00:28:47.780
As we diet to lose weight, the
body gets very angry with us,

00:28:47.780 --> 00:28:49.770
and it rebounds, usually
at a higher set point.

00:28:49.770 --> 00:28:53.090
So weight cycling leads to a
consistent increase in weight

00:28:53.090 --> 00:28:54.440
over time.

00:28:54.440 --> 00:28:56.270
And then maternal
and paternal obesity

00:28:56.270 --> 00:28:58.260
can affect this as well.

00:28:58.260 --> 00:29:01.010
So I'm going to take you
back to my childhood,

00:29:01.010 --> 00:29:03.360
because I want to shift into
talking about weight bias.

00:29:03.360 --> 00:29:04.776
And I think this
is very important

00:29:04.776 --> 00:29:07.490
because weight bias, I think,
does preclude our ability

00:29:07.490 --> 00:29:11.270
to focus on this disease and
the treatment of this disease.

00:29:11.270 --> 00:29:15.260
This is me back when I was
like, I don't know, six.

00:29:15.260 --> 00:29:17.150
This is my little sister.

00:29:17.150 --> 00:29:20.240
My little sister is also
37, but I talk about her

00:29:20.240 --> 00:29:23.066
like she's a child.

00:29:23.066 --> 00:29:24.440
The reason why I
bring this up is

00:29:24.440 --> 00:29:27.300
because at a recent
obesity convention,

00:29:27.300 --> 00:29:29.780
I was approached by a
childhood friend of mine

00:29:29.780 --> 00:29:32.730
from about this time
frame, who came up to me,

00:29:32.730 --> 00:29:34.980
and she said, well, Fatima,
I'm trying to talk to you.

00:29:34.980 --> 00:29:36.422
And I'm like, OK.

00:29:36.422 --> 00:29:38.630
Different people kept trying
to pull me aside to talk

00:29:38.630 --> 00:29:39.838
about other different issues.

00:29:39.838 --> 00:29:41.540
She kept trying to get me alone.

00:29:41.540 --> 00:29:44.360
Couldn't figure
out why this was.

00:29:44.360 --> 00:29:46.730
And she was like,
well, Fatima, I just

00:29:46.730 --> 00:29:49.490
want you to know that there
is a reason why I've always

00:29:49.490 --> 00:29:53.720
been relatively standoffish
as it relates to your.

00:29:53.720 --> 00:29:54.740
I just had not noticed.

00:29:54.740 --> 00:29:56.573
I just thought that's
how she was since I've

00:29:56.573 --> 00:29:58.390
known her since I was six.

00:29:58.390 --> 00:29:59.180
I didn't know.

00:29:59.180 --> 00:30:01.040
So she was like, do
you know why that is?

00:30:01.040 --> 00:30:02.870
And I was like, no I'm not.

00:30:02.870 --> 00:30:05.630
She's like, well, you came
up to me in dance class

00:30:05.630 --> 00:30:08.960
when we were about six,
and you called me fat.

00:30:08.960 --> 00:30:10.370
Right.

00:30:10.370 --> 00:30:13.010
I don't like to be
vulnerable on stage, either.

00:30:13.010 --> 00:30:16.330
So I was like, well, I'm sure
she remembers that correctly.

00:30:16.330 --> 00:30:18.440
I'm devastated that
as the person that's

00:30:18.440 --> 00:30:21.920
supposed to be undoing weight
bias, that this has impacted

00:30:21.920 --> 00:30:23.930
her life so much
that she has gone

00:30:23.930 --> 00:30:27.770
into a career in obesity
medicine and academics.

00:30:27.770 --> 00:30:31.480
But she told me-- this is what
was the most striking portion

00:30:31.480 --> 00:30:33.200
of what she said--

00:30:33.200 --> 00:30:36.080
she said, well I feel as though
if you're capable of change,

00:30:36.080 --> 00:30:38.434
anyone is capable of change.

00:30:38.434 --> 00:30:41.176
[LAUGHTER]

00:30:41.176 --> 00:30:44.720
So I think a choked back
a tear when that happened.

00:30:44.720 --> 00:30:48.560
But I think that it
was a point well taken.

00:30:48.560 --> 00:30:53.470
And it led me to recognize that
something that I did or said--

00:30:53.470 --> 00:30:55.130
I was very apologetic
that I said

00:30:55.130 --> 00:30:56.840
this when I was six years old--

00:30:56.840 --> 00:30:59.420
had a huge impact on her life.

00:30:59.420 --> 00:31:01.410
For her, it ended up
being a positive thing.

00:31:01.410 --> 00:31:06.380
But in any way, you can tell
that this has a huge impact.

00:31:06.380 --> 00:31:08.080
So that's my story.

00:31:08.080 --> 00:31:10.250
Now let's look at bias
in Western societies.

00:31:10.250 --> 00:31:12.410
And bias that we talk
about, we don't usually

00:31:12.410 --> 00:31:13.647
hear much about weight bias.

00:31:13.647 --> 00:31:15.230
I mean although, I
think it's becoming

00:31:15.230 --> 00:31:16.730
more of a prominent issue.

00:31:16.730 --> 00:31:18.640
We hear more about race bias.

00:31:18.640 --> 00:31:21.467
So if you did a Google
search back in 2012--

00:31:21.467 --> 00:31:24.050
this was actually not reported
on in the Washington Post until

00:31:24.050 --> 00:31:25.370
2016--

00:31:25.370 --> 00:31:27.740
if you Googled young
black male, these

00:31:27.740 --> 00:31:31.095
were the images that came up.

00:31:31.095 --> 00:31:32.720
They supposedly
changed the algorithm--

00:31:32.720 --> 00:31:35.600
I didn't try this
before this talk.

00:31:35.600 --> 00:31:40.420
When you Googled young teens
without race qualifiers,

00:31:40.420 --> 00:31:42.380
you got kind of happy
looking pictures

00:31:42.380 --> 00:31:45.050
like this, which is
very, very different

00:31:45.050 --> 00:31:47.000
from what you see at the top.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:50.570
Glamour, back in 2012,
wanted to give adjectives

00:31:50.570 --> 00:31:53.840
to describe how we
think of young women

00:31:53.840 --> 00:31:57.590
that either are lean versus
those that have obesity.

00:31:57.590 --> 00:32:00.050
And so you can see these
adjectives that are often

00:32:00.050 --> 00:32:02.990
used to describe a lean woman--

00:32:02.990 --> 00:32:05.420
seated, ambitious,
confident, mean.

00:32:05.420 --> 00:32:07.880
For someone that has
obesity, the presumption

00:32:07.880 --> 00:32:11.900
is she's undisciplined,
insecure, giving, lazy,

00:32:11.900 --> 00:32:14.750
passive, nice.

00:32:14.750 --> 00:32:16.040
And so we do have these.

00:32:16.040 --> 00:32:20.020
I would say that what's become
the most common form of bias

00:32:20.020 --> 00:32:22.520
that's accepted is weight bias.

00:32:22.520 --> 00:32:26.250
Really, you know these are kind
of terms that we think about.

00:32:26.250 --> 00:32:28.880
So how early does
weight bias begin?

00:32:28.880 --> 00:32:32.210
And it's going to be
shocking to recognize

00:32:32.210 --> 00:32:36.290
that we start seeing weight bias
as early as 32 months of age.

00:32:36.290 --> 00:32:40.670
In this particular study, they
looked at 70 mother and child

00:32:40.670 --> 00:32:45.020
pairs, where they showed
the infants pictures.

00:32:45.020 --> 00:32:47.060
And those that were
11 months of age

00:32:47.060 --> 00:32:49.680
had a preference for looking
at figures with obesity.

00:32:49.680 --> 00:32:51.860
So this is is kind of the
pictures they were shown.

00:32:51.860 --> 00:32:53.930
By the time they got
to 32 months however,

00:32:53.930 --> 00:32:55.880
they changed to
going to the more

00:32:55.880 --> 00:32:57.890
average or lean individuals.

00:32:57.890 --> 00:33:00.920
And that was specifically
based on the maternal's

00:33:00.920 --> 00:33:02.300
anti-fat attitudes.

00:33:02.300 --> 00:33:06.560
So if the mom had significant
anti-fat attitudes,

00:33:06.560 --> 00:33:09.950
we saw a significant
shift with average age

00:33:09.950 --> 00:33:12.110
of 32 months of these
children beginning

00:33:12.110 --> 00:33:16.470
to demonstrate weight bias
against those that had obesity.

00:33:16.470 --> 00:33:18.154
Now this study was
a study that was

00:33:18.154 --> 00:33:20.570
done looking at three-year-old
children and their parents,

00:33:20.570 --> 00:33:22.130
279.

00:33:22.130 --> 00:33:24.380
And they conducted
interviews of the children.

00:33:24.380 --> 00:33:26.900
And what they saw was that
over the time of the study,

00:33:26.900 --> 00:33:29.270
there were more
negative attitudes

00:33:29.270 --> 00:33:31.820
towards large
bodied individuals,

00:33:31.820 --> 00:33:34.130
and there was awareness
of weight loss strategies

00:33:34.130 --> 00:33:36.680
that were really coming more
from the father, actually,

00:33:36.680 --> 00:33:37.890
in this situation.

00:33:37.890 --> 00:33:39.890
So this is a little bit
of a deviation from what

00:33:39.890 --> 00:33:42.440
you saw in the previous
study, but the previous only

00:33:42.440 --> 00:33:44.210
looked at mom and
children, whereas these

00:33:44.210 --> 00:33:48.000
looked at both mom,
dad, and their children.

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:51.920
So here, we're transmitting
through social cues, weight

00:33:51.920 --> 00:33:53.944
bias.

00:33:53.944 --> 00:33:54.860
This is a great study.

00:33:54.860 --> 00:33:57.320
So this looked at weight
teething and adolescence,

00:33:57.320 --> 00:34:00.650
and what that meant with regards
to weight related outcomes

00:34:00.650 --> 00:34:02.056
in adult adulthood.

00:34:02.056 --> 00:34:03.430
What they did was
they identified

00:34:03.430 --> 00:34:05.520
whether weight based
teasing, and adolescent

00:34:05.520 --> 00:34:08.270
predicted adverse eating,
and weight related outcomes

00:34:08.270 --> 00:34:11.000
15 years later.

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:13.600
They determined whether
the teasing source,

00:34:13.600 --> 00:34:16.489
the source was either
the peers or the family,

00:34:16.489 --> 00:34:18.110
affected these outcomes.

00:34:18.110 --> 00:34:21.889
And they collected this
data for 1,830 individuals

00:34:21.889 --> 00:34:26.600
from 1999 to 2015 in diverse
group of adolescents.

00:34:26.600 --> 00:34:28.639
So they looked at
race and ethnicity

00:34:28.639 --> 00:34:30.650
also along these lines.

00:34:30.650 --> 00:34:33.889
What they found was that weight
based teasing in adolescence

00:34:33.889 --> 00:34:36.179
did predict higher
body mass index

00:34:36.179 --> 00:34:38.360
and obesity 15 years later.

00:34:38.360 --> 00:34:41.540
So what they found was
that BMI increased.

00:34:41.540 --> 00:34:44.659
That led to binge eating,
more dieting, unhealthy weight

00:34:44.659 --> 00:34:47.659
control, which then
affected the body image.

00:34:47.659 --> 00:34:53.030
Now for females, both peers
and family based teasing

00:34:53.030 --> 00:34:56.540
had implications for leading
to increased disorders,

00:34:56.540 --> 00:34:59.420
eating, and having a higher BMI.

00:34:59.420 --> 00:35:02.294
Whereas for males,
only peer based teasing

00:35:02.294 --> 00:35:03.210
seemed to affect them.

00:35:03.210 --> 00:35:06.680
They weren't quite as moved by
what their family was doing.

00:35:06.680 --> 00:35:08.960
But regardless of who
the teasing is from,

00:35:08.960 --> 00:35:12.590
you can see that what a patient
experiences in adolescence does

00:35:12.590 --> 00:35:16.710
have huge implications for what
they experience in adulthood.

00:35:16.710 --> 00:35:19.160
So let's look at weight
bias internalization

00:35:19.160 --> 00:35:21.350
and metabolic syndrome.

00:35:21.350 --> 00:35:24.110
When we look at blood pressure,
waist circumference, fasting,

00:35:24.110 --> 00:35:27.560
blood sugar, triglycerides,
which is a type of cholesterol,

00:35:27.560 --> 00:35:29.570
and then HDL, which
is a good cholesterol,

00:35:29.570 --> 00:35:34.720
measured in 178 adults with
obesity in a weight loss trial.

00:35:34.720 --> 00:35:37.520
Of these adults, they
completed a weight

00:35:37.520 --> 00:35:41.500
by internalization scale, and
a patient health questionnaire.

00:35:41.500 --> 00:35:44.425
32% met criteria for
metabolic syndrome,

00:35:44.425 --> 00:35:46.550
which means they have a
predilection for developing

00:35:46.550 --> 00:35:48.630
type 2 diabetes.

00:35:48.630 --> 00:35:51.470
And this high weight
based internalization

00:35:51.470 --> 00:35:55.160
predicted the greater odds
of having metabolic syndrome

00:35:55.160 --> 00:35:58.140
and high triglycerides, which
is one of our bad cholesterols.

00:35:58.140 --> 00:36:00.740
So even though it just
seems like it's not

00:36:00.740 --> 00:36:03.140
very hurtful to
individuals, this study

00:36:03.140 --> 00:36:05.960
demonstrated that it could
be very hurtful and harmful.

00:36:08.760 --> 00:36:11.410
And also, when we look at mental
health of persons with obesity

00:36:11.410 --> 00:36:14.630
who experience bias,
physiologic stress

00:36:14.630 --> 00:36:18.320
leads to weight gain, which
then leads to disordered eating,

00:36:18.320 --> 00:36:20.730
and then, maladaptive behaviors.

00:36:20.730 --> 00:36:23.660
So it affects the mental
health of these individuals.

00:36:23.660 --> 00:36:25.820
Now in terms of
overcoming weight stigma

00:36:25.820 --> 00:36:27.760
and the treatment
of obesity, there

00:36:27.760 --> 00:36:30.410
are many different areas
that we need to work on.

00:36:30.410 --> 00:36:32.930
First, when stress
is involved, we

00:36:32.930 --> 00:36:35.270
start seeing issues
that affect food

00:36:35.270 --> 00:36:37.160
eating and physical
activity behaviors.

00:36:37.160 --> 00:36:40.070
We start seeing binge eating,
increased caloric consumption,

00:36:40.070 --> 00:36:41.840
or maladaptive weight
control, meaning

00:36:41.840 --> 00:36:44.600
using methods that aren't going
to lead to long term weight

00:36:44.600 --> 00:36:46.370
regulation.

00:36:46.370 --> 00:36:48.770
Disordered eating, lower
motivation for exercise,

00:36:48.770 --> 00:36:50.650
less physical activity.

00:36:50.650 --> 00:36:53.720
There are actual physiologic
response to weight stigma.

00:36:53.720 --> 00:36:56.660
We have increased
levels of cortisol, CRP,

00:36:56.660 --> 00:36:58.810
these are stress
hormones within the body.

00:36:58.810 --> 00:37:01.730
A1C, which is
average blood sugar.

00:37:01.730 --> 00:37:03.969
And also, elevated
blood pressure.

00:37:03.969 --> 00:37:05.510
With regards to
health care services,

00:37:05.510 --> 00:37:07.100
they have poorer
treatment adherence.

00:37:07.100 --> 00:37:09.170
They don't trust their
health providers.

00:37:09.170 --> 00:37:11.030
They avoid follow up care.

00:37:11.030 --> 00:37:12.920
They delay in preventive
health screenings.

00:37:12.920 --> 00:37:15.380
And there's poor communication.

00:37:15.380 --> 00:37:16.820
Psychological
health distress, we

00:37:16.820 --> 00:37:19.920
see depression, anxiety, low
self-esteem, poor body image,

00:37:19.920 --> 00:37:22.340
substance abuse,
and suicidality.

00:37:22.340 --> 00:37:24.260
And then physiologic
health or distress,

00:37:24.260 --> 00:37:27.620
we see poor glycemic control,
less effect of chronic disease

00:37:27.620 --> 00:37:30.710
self management, more
advanced and poorly controlled

00:37:30.710 --> 00:37:34.370
chronic disease, and lower
health related quality of life.

00:37:34.370 --> 00:37:38.060
So you can see that this weight
stigma has huge implications

00:37:38.060 --> 00:37:39.660
for the individual.

00:37:39.660 --> 00:37:41.690
Now we're going to go
quickly into looking

00:37:41.690 --> 00:37:43.370
at obesity treatments.

00:37:43.370 --> 00:37:45.500
What do we do for those
that have obesity.

00:37:45.500 --> 00:37:47.750
We talked about
93.4 million adults

00:37:47.750 --> 00:37:50.090
having obesity here
in the United States.

00:37:50.090 --> 00:37:52.670
What do I do in the clinic
setting to treat them,

00:37:52.670 --> 00:37:55.310
and what guidelines
is it based on.

00:37:55.310 --> 00:37:57.860
So here, we're looking
at BMI category,

00:37:57.860 --> 00:38:01.200
and we're looking at those that
fall into having overweight,

00:38:01.200 --> 00:38:03.530
which would be 25 to 29.9.

00:38:03.530 --> 00:38:06.320
And then class 1, mild,
class 2, moderate,

00:38:06.320 --> 00:38:09.030
or class 3, severe obesity.

00:38:09.030 --> 00:38:10.940
Now you can see diet,
physical activity,

00:38:10.940 --> 00:38:15.200
and behavioral therapy, we
can use across the spectrum

00:38:15.200 --> 00:38:16.820
of weight class.

00:38:16.820 --> 00:38:19.066
With regards to pharmacotherapy,
meaning medications

00:38:19.066 --> 00:38:21.440
we use for weight loss, we
don't begin to entertain those

00:38:21.440 --> 00:38:27.080
until we have a BMI of 27 with
co-morbidities, meaning heart

00:38:27.080 --> 00:38:30.627
disease, type 2 diabetes,
obstructive sleep apnea.

00:38:30.627 --> 00:38:32.210
And then weight loss
surgery, we start

00:38:32.210 --> 00:38:35.440
to really get into when we get
into class 1, 2, and 3 obesity.

00:38:35.440 --> 00:38:36.980
The current criteria,
technically,

00:38:36.980 --> 00:38:41.150
is class 2 with
co-morbidities or for those

00:38:41.150 --> 00:38:44.000
that have a BMI an
excess or equal to 40

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:46.280
without co-morbidities.

00:38:46.280 --> 00:38:49.800
So let's first explore common
weight promoting drugs.

00:38:49.800 --> 00:38:52.520
These are medications that
are prescribed by doctors,

00:38:52.520 --> 00:38:54.890
which lead to weight gain.

00:38:54.890 --> 00:38:57.470
I like to do a laundry list
here with all of my patients,

00:38:57.470 --> 00:39:00.240
and I ask them if they've taken
lithium, Depakote, Tegretol,

00:39:00.240 --> 00:39:02.710
Alexis, Cymbalta, Effexor,
Paxil, Prozac, Ambien,

00:39:02.710 --> 00:39:05.240
Trazodone, Lunesta, Gabapentin,
Glyburide, Glipizide,

00:39:05.240 --> 00:39:07.160
Glimepiride,
Atenolol, Metoprolol,

00:39:07.160 --> 00:39:09.794
Propanolol, long term insulin,
or long term Prednisone.

00:39:09.794 --> 00:39:12.210
And if they are taking any of
those for a month or longer,

00:39:12.210 --> 00:39:13.876
there's a high
likelihood that there was

00:39:13.876 --> 00:39:15.570
a weight contributing factor.

00:39:15.570 --> 00:39:17.070
I've put them up
here on the screen.

00:39:17.070 --> 00:39:20.060
You might have seen, I
use the generic names.

00:39:20.060 --> 00:39:22.350
But if you've been on
any of these medications,

00:39:22.350 --> 00:39:23.775
and noticed a shift
in weight, you

00:39:23.775 --> 00:39:25.400
might want to discuss
with your doctor,

00:39:25.400 --> 00:39:29.150
because I can tell you that in
medical school, in residency--

00:39:29.150 --> 00:39:30.950
and my fellowship, we
did learn about this

00:39:30.950 --> 00:39:32.900
because I did an obesity
medicine fellowship--

00:39:32.900 --> 00:39:34.490
we don't learn
about the likelihood

00:39:34.490 --> 00:39:36.740
that a lot of these drugs
lead to weight gain,

00:39:36.740 --> 00:39:39.650
and that we might need
to use alternatives

00:39:39.650 --> 00:39:42.860
to control the weight
gain that is occurring

00:39:42.860 --> 00:39:45.540
from these medications.

00:39:45.540 --> 00:39:47.390
So what I do is when
a patient comes in,

00:39:47.390 --> 00:39:48.950
I investigate whether
medications are

00:39:48.950 --> 00:39:50.780
a likely source of weight gain.

00:39:50.780 --> 00:39:54.030
If I can discontinue the drug,
that would be my first step.

00:39:54.030 --> 00:39:56.960
But if I'm unable to discontinue
it because I'm treating,

00:39:56.960 --> 00:40:01.340
let's say, a psychiatric
illness like bipolar disorder,

00:40:01.340 --> 00:40:04.970
I then need to utilize
weight-loss medications

00:40:04.970 --> 00:40:08.182
to control the weight
gain that they have.

00:40:08.182 --> 00:40:10.640
So you guys are like, weight
loss medications, really, they

00:40:10.640 --> 00:40:11.180
use those?

00:40:11.180 --> 00:40:13.070
Yes, we do.

00:40:13.070 --> 00:40:15.170
And there are three classes
of medications-- those

00:40:15.170 --> 00:40:17.180
that act centrally,
meaning in the brain

00:40:17.180 --> 00:40:19.175
to impair dietary intake.

00:40:19.175 --> 00:40:21.050
Those that act more
peripherally, so out here

00:40:21.050 --> 00:40:23.390
in the periphery, to
impair absorption.

00:40:23.390 --> 00:40:26.690
And those that increase
energy expenditure.

00:40:26.690 --> 00:40:29.780
These are the FDA approved
anti-obesity pharmacotherapy

00:40:29.780 --> 00:40:31.370
agents as of today.

00:40:31.370 --> 00:40:32.820
You'll notice
things with a star.

00:40:32.820 --> 00:40:35.090
These are approved for long
term weight regulation.

00:40:35.090 --> 00:40:40.490
And many of the star agents
were approved from 2012 to now.

00:40:40.490 --> 00:40:43.290
Phentermine is a long term drug
that you might have heard of,

00:40:43.290 --> 00:40:45.650
and people get really scared
when they hear Phentermine

00:40:45.650 --> 00:40:48.440
because fen-phen, which was
withdrawn from the market,

00:40:48.440 --> 00:40:50.400
and it did include Phentermine.

00:40:50.400 --> 00:40:52.850
But the fen that was
removed from the market

00:40:52.850 --> 00:40:56.060
was fenfluramine-- that's
the F-E-N-- fenfluramine.

00:40:56.060 --> 00:40:57.770
It caused heart valve issues.

00:40:57.770 --> 00:40:59.570
Phentermine has
remained continuously

00:40:59.570 --> 00:41:01.945
on the market since 1959.

00:41:01.945 --> 00:41:03.320
Phentermine
Topiramate in combos,

00:41:03.320 --> 00:41:05.630
so the most effective
drug that we

00:41:05.630 --> 00:41:08.550
have in the general population
for weight regulation.

00:41:08.550 --> 00:41:10.910
Bupropion,
Wellbutrin-- people are

00:41:10.910 --> 00:41:13.610
used to hearing that name--
and Naltrexone is very commonly

00:41:13.610 --> 00:41:14.490
used.

00:41:14.490 --> 00:41:17.850
Naltrexone is what we call
an opioid antagonists.

00:41:17.850 --> 00:41:20.300
So I always warn my patients
when they go on this medicine

00:41:20.300 --> 00:41:23.350
that if they need opioid
medications for let's

00:41:23.350 --> 00:41:26.840
say, a surgery, then we would
need to remove that drug.

00:41:26.840 --> 00:41:29.580
And also, I would warn them
that the stigma surrounding

00:41:29.580 --> 00:41:34.694
the opioid epidemic here
in the United States

00:41:34.694 --> 00:41:36.360
is such that when
people see Naltrexone,

00:41:36.360 --> 00:41:37.943
they will immediately
assume that they

00:41:37.943 --> 00:41:40.830
had an opioid issue, as opposed
to recognizing that it's

00:41:40.830 --> 00:41:43.200
used for weight regulation.

00:41:43.200 --> 00:41:44.940
These are other
anti-obesity agents

00:41:44.940 --> 00:41:48.270
that I might utilize that
aren't necessarily FDA approved.

00:41:48.270 --> 00:41:50.560
You may have seen them
in combination approved,

00:41:50.560 --> 00:41:53.160
not approved as
individual agents.

00:41:53.160 --> 00:41:55.856
But we will utilize
these readily.

00:41:55.856 --> 00:41:57.480
Now with weight loss
surgery, we talked

00:41:57.480 --> 00:41:59.550
about using weight
loss surgery for those

00:41:59.550 --> 00:42:03.150
that have been trying
to lose weight, still

00:42:03.150 --> 00:42:05.580
struggle with moderate
to severe obesity.

00:42:05.580 --> 00:42:07.800
For those that have class
2 or moderate obesity,

00:42:07.800 --> 00:42:11.100
they do need to have a
serious co-morbidity of type 2

00:42:11.100 --> 00:42:13.950
diabetes, heart disease,
or obstructive sleep apnea.

00:42:13.950 --> 00:42:16.410
Prior unsuccessful
weight loss attempts,

00:42:16.410 --> 00:42:18.760
acceptable operative
risk, and the ability

00:42:18.760 --> 00:42:21.960
to participate long term
treatment and follow up.

00:42:21.960 --> 00:42:24.330
And an understanding of the
operation and the lifestyle

00:42:24.330 --> 00:42:27.760
changes needed to
sustain weight loss.

00:42:27.760 --> 00:42:30.870
These are the two most
commonly performed procedures

00:42:30.870 --> 00:42:32.160
here in the United States.

00:42:32.160 --> 00:42:36.120
The sleeve gastrectomy here
is the most common procedure.

00:42:36.120 --> 00:42:38.400
People think that the
bypass is the most common,

00:42:38.400 --> 00:42:40.680
but that has not been the
most common procedure here

00:42:40.680 --> 00:42:43.360
in the United States at least
for the last seven years.

00:42:43.360 --> 00:42:44.710
So this is the most common.

00:42:44.710 --> 00:42:47.310
So you might wonder, oh, it's
because the stomach is smaller.

00:42:47.310 --> 00:42:49.380
No, it's because we
remove the stomach,

00:42:49.380 --> 00:42:52.440
and ghrelin, which you guys
remember, which is orexigenic,

00:42:52.440 --> 00:42:55.560
or promoted appetite,
is housed here

00:42:55.560 --> 00:42:57.300
in the fundus of the stomach.

00:42:57.300 --> 00:42:59.610
Same with the Roux-en-Y
gastric bypass.

00:42:59.610 --> 00:43:03.720
We are circumventing all of
this portion of the stomach

00:43:03.720 --> 00:43:05.790
and the beginning portion
of the small intestine.

00:43:05.790 --> 00:43:08.610
When someone eats something,
they go and bypass

00:43:08.610 --> 00:43:12.700
that portion, and it comes
right into the small intestine.

00:43:12.700 --> 00:43:13.950
So it's not really the sides--

00:43:13.950 --> 00:43:17.370
it's the change in the brain
and gut communication that leads

00:43:17.370 --> 00:43:18.454
to the weight loss change.

00:43:18.454 --> 00:43:20.869
And I'll take you through a
few cases, and then we'll end,

00:43:20.869 --> 00:43:22.960
and I'll entertain
some questions.

00:43:22.960 --> 00:43:25.649
So I should be finished
relatively soon.

00:43:25.649 --> 00:43:27.440
But I want to give you
guys a few patients.

00:43:27.440 --> 00:43:29.574
I thought about whether
or not to do this,

00:43:29.574 --> 00:43:30.990
but I think it's
important for you

00:43:30.990 --> 00:43:33.980
to understand what it
looks like in real life.

00:43:33.980 --> 00:43:35.550
So this is a
54-year-old one that

00:43:35.550 --> 00:43:38.359
came into me with hypertension--
untreated hypertension--

00:43:38.359 --> 00:43:39.150
migraine headaches.

00:43:39.150 --> 00:43:41.340
She had reflux,
irritable bowel syndrome,

00:43:41.340 --> 00:43:42.330
and metabolic syndrome.

00:43:42.330 --> 00:43:45.050
She retained 20 pounds with
each of her two pregnancies,

00:43:45.050 --> 00:43:47.610
and she's tried many
commercial programs, which

00:43:47.610 --> 00:43:49.800
lead to 20 pounds of
unsustainable weight loss

00:43:49.800 --> 00:43:50.829
with each attempt.

00:43:50.829 --> 00:43:53.370
Her most significant weight loss
was with the use of fen-phen

00:43:53.370 --> 00:43:54.210
in the 1990's.

00:43:54.210 --> 00:43:56.479
She lost over 50 pounds over
the course of six months.

00:43:56.479 --> 00:43:58.770
She comes in to me specifically
interest of weight loss

00:43:58.770 --> 00:44:01.740
medications, plus
behavioral therapy.

00:44:01.740 --> 00:44:04.410
These graphs-- you'll see
a couple more after this.

00:44:04.410 --> 00:44:05.910
We have weight in pounds here.

00:44:05.910 --> 00:44:07.890
We have BMI or body
mass index here.

00:44:07.890 --> 00:44:09.480
And we have time here.

00:44:09.480 --> 00:44:11.280
So you can see for
this individual is

00:44:11.280 --> 00:44:13.930
that every time she would
lose that 20 pounds,

00:44:13.930 --> 00:44:15.070
she would gain it back.

00:44:15.070 --> 00:44:17.070
She's lose the 20 pounds,
she gained it back.

00:44:17.070 --> 00:44:20.040
So of course, she comes to
see me here at a BMI of 40.

00:44:20.040 --> 00:44:23.100
And she has a significant
drop to a BMI of 31.

00:44:23.100 --> 00:44:25.350
I'm going to have you guys
yell out from the audience.

00:44:25.350 --> 00:44:28.900
What do you guys
think I did for her?

00:44:28.900 --> 00:44:29.860
Weight loss surgery.

00:44:29.860 --> 00:44:30.430
Absolutely.

00:44:30.430 --> 00:44:31.300
That's a good guess.

00:44:31.300 --> 00:44:32.935
Anyone else want to
guess differently?

00:44:35.730 --> 00:44:36.730
This was all behavioral.

00:44:36.730 --> 00:44:39.450
Now this shocked me just
as much as it shocks you,

00:44:39.450 --> 00:44:41.040
because she'd try, right?

00:44:41.040 --> 00:44:43.140
She tried and lost,
tried and lost.

00:44:43.140 --> 00:44:44.940
And for some reason,
when she came in

00:44:44.940 --> 00:44:46.890
and did our Healthy
Habits for Life program,

00:44:46.890 --> 00:44:49.260
she was able to
achieve a BMI 31.

00:44:49.260 --> 00:44:52.530
Now you can see that she's
stabilized here at a BMI of 30,

00:44:52.530 --> 00:44:55.260
and she's had some
subsequent drops.

00:44:55.260 --> 00:44:58.330
And that was when I added
medication and to keep her

00:44:58.330 --> 00:45:00.270
at this different set point.

00:45:00.270 --> 00:45:01.920
You can see that she comes down.

00:45:01.920 --> 00:45:05.640
But a typical graph here--
behavior, medication, surgery--

00:45:05.640 --> 00:45:07.380
is they'll come down,
and they rebound.

00:45:07.380 --> 00:45:10.950
I caught her when she rebounded,
I added another medicine.

00:45:10.950 --> 00:45:14.160
And so she is now here
with two different drugs,

00:45:14.160 --> 00:45:18.390
on board for the
utilization for weight loss.

00:45:18.390 --> 00:45:19.440
Let's take you to case 2.

00:45:19.440 --> 00:45:20.680
This is a 57-year-old woman.

00:45:20.680 --> 00:45:23.013
You might be like, why am I
using all 50-year-old women.

00:45:23.013 --> 00:45:25.500
The typical patient that
presents for weight management

00:45:25.500 --> 00:45:28.950
is a Caucasian
post-menopausal woman.

00:45:28.950 --> 00:45:30.942
That's who we will
typically see in the office.

00:45:30.942 --> 00:45:33.150
Those are the people that
are like, what is going on,

00:45:33.150 --> 00:45:35.860
I'm doing all the right
things, why am I struggling.

00:45:35.860 --> 00:45:37.860
OK, so this woman had a
history of dyslipidemia,

00:45:37.860 --> 00:45:40.151
which means high cholesterol,
breast cancer, high blood

00:45:40.151 --> 00:45:41.660
pressure, depression.

00:45:41.660 --> 00:45:43.560
You can see her diet--
pretty good, right?

00:45:43.560 --> 00:45:45.690
Brown rice, cashews,
goat cheese.

00:45:45.690 --> 00:45:47.180
She eats fish.

00:45:47.180 --> 00:45:52.050
She eats some nuts, and
spinach, salad for dinner.

00:45:52.050 --> 00:45:53.440
She exercises quite a bit.

00:45:53.440 --> 00:45:56.500
She does cardio interval
circuit three times per week.

00:45:56.500 --> 00:45:57.812
Two videos for a half hour.

00:45:57.812 --> 00:45:58.770
She does yoga at night.

00:45:58.770 --> 00:45:59.894
She sleeps for eight hours.

00:45:59.894 --> 00:46:02.970
So you're kind of like, what
do I do differently, right?

00:46:02.970 --> 00:46:03.810
She's doing a lot.

00:46:03.810 --> 00:46:05.370
So remember, the
same graph, right?

00:46:05.370 --> 00:46:06.880
Now it's graph.

00:46:06.880 --> 00:46:08.840
Weight in pounds on this axis.

00:46:08.840 --> 00:46:11.520
BMI, body mass index here.

00:46:11.520 --> 00:46:13.680
She starts off at a BMI of 56.

00:46:13.680 --> 00:46:15.300
Pretty severe obesity, right?

00:46:15.300 --> 00:46:18.840
BMIs in excess of 40
are considered severe.

00:46:18.840 --> 00:46:21.660
And she has this lovely
drop to a BMI of 33.

00:46:21.660 --> 00:46:23.190
This is back-- you can see--

00:46:23.190 --> 00:46:25.470
many years ago, 2003.

00:46:25.470 --> 00:46:30.366
And what do you think
drove about this change?

00:46:30.366 --> 00:46:32.380
Everybody's whispering.

00:46:32.380 --> 00:46:33.140
Surgery.

00:46:33.140 --> 00:46:35.060
That's a reasonable thought.

00:46:35.060 --> 00:46:37.362
This was medication.

00:46:37.362 --> 00:46:39.570
Now you might be like, wow,
that's pretty impressive.

00:46:39.570 --> 00:46:40.861
That's why she makes my graphs.

00:46:40.861 --> 00:46:42.870
But she has a rebound.

00:46:42.870 --> 00:46:44.600
So she comes back up
to this BMI of 40.

00:46:44.600 --> 00:46:48.470
Her BMI 40 is not
that BMI of 56,

00:46:48.470 --> 00:46:50.990
but something happens, and
it drives her back down

00:46:50.990 --> 00:46:53.810
to this BMI of 33.

00:46:53.810 --> 00:46:58.700
So that was back in
2005, end of 2005.

00:46:58.700 --> 00:46:59.767
What drove her back?

00:46:59.767 --> 00:47:01.850
I mean, she goes from 40
to 33-- not a huge shift,

00:47:01.850 --> 00:47:03.110
but you know--

00:47:03.110 --> 00:47:05.920
what do you guys think?

00:47:05.920 --> 00:47:06.850
No, she dropped.

00:47:06.850 --> 00:47:09.270
She [INAUDIBLE] the drop.

00:47:09.270 --> 00:47:10.790
Menopause and drop--

00:47:10.790 --> 00:47:14.060
I can tell you, my
patients will love that.

00:47:14.060 --> 00:47:15.890
What do you guys think?

00:47:15.890 --> 00:47:18.790
You said something,
what did you say?

00:47:18.790 --> 00:47:20.230
Romantic?

00:47:20.230 --> 00:47:22.460
A romantic involvement--
that's the first.

00:47:22.460 --> 00:47:24.950
I like that answer.

00:47:24.950 --> 00:47:28.110
That's when she had her
Roux-en-Y gastric bypass.

00:47:28.110 --> 00:47:29.900
So her surgery didn't
really do very much,

00:47:29.900 --> 00:47:31.191
would you guys agree with that?

00:47:31.191 --> 00:47:33.484
Very, very low
amount of efficacy.

00:47:33.484 --> 00:47:35.150
She comes in, of
course, to see me here,

00:47:35.150 --> 00:47:37.442
because that's when patients
like to come in to me.

00:47:37.442 --> 00:47:39.650
I would have loved to have
seen her anywhere in here,

00:47:39.650 --> 00:47:41.900
but that's just not what I get.

00:47:41.900 --> 00:47:44.030
So she comes into
the BMI of 44.5,

00:47:44.030 --> 00:47:47.130
she gets driven down
to a BMI of 28.5.

00:47:47.130 --> 00:47:50.920
And what do you guys think
I did for her at this point?

00:47:50.920 --> 00:47:51.810
Behavior?

00:47:51.810 --> 00:47:53.310
You guys are coming
on to something.

00:47:53.310 --> 00:47:56.040
I will not do anything until
the behavior is controlled.

00:47:56.040 --> 00:47:56.550
What else?

00:47:59.180 --> 00:48:00.800
I put her back on
the drug she was on.

00:48:00.800 --> 00:48:04.514
So her doctor stopped these
medications because he said,

00:48:04.514 --> 00:48:06.680
oh, well, you can't be on
the medications long term.

00:48:06.680 --> 00:48:09.096
Remember, I told you these are
approved for long term use.

00:48:09.096 --> 00:48:10.720
When we're using
medications to treat

00:48:10.720 --> 00:48:14.050
a chronic disease, this
chronic disease being obesity,

00:48:14.050 --> 00:48:16.450
when I withdraw those
agents, the brain

00:48:16.450 --> 00:48:19.780
gets back to where it was, and
you will regain the weight.

00:48:19.780 --> 00:48:21.790
So I do have to keep
her on these long term.

00:48:21.790 --> 00:48:25.710
So that's important for me
to discuss with my patients.

00:48:25.710 --> 00:48:27.280
I have a 49-year-old
Hispanic woman

00:48:27.280 --> 00:48:29.420
coming in with the issue
of anxiety and depression.

00:48:29.420 --> 00:48:31.480
She has a ventricular
tachycardia,

00:48:31.480 --> 00:48:32.860
which means that
her heart beats,

00:48:32.860 --> 00:48:35.410
and she had an ablation,
which controlled that.

00:48:35.410 --> 00:48:38.290
She has mixed connection of
tissue disease, hypertension,

00:48:38.290 --> 00:48:39.360
reflux.

00:48:39.360 --> 00:48:41.919
This is her diet, this
is her exercise regimen.

00:48:41.919 --> 00:48:43.960
She noticed that her weight
gain became prominent

00:48:43.960 --> 00:48:44.750
after childbirth.

00:48:44.750 --> 00:48:47.669
She gained 10 pounds with
each of her six pregnancies.

00:48:47.669 --> 00:48:49.210
She also noticed
that she gain weight

00:48:49.210 --> 00:48:51.130
when she stopped
smoking, and when

00:48:51.130 --> 00:48:54.080
she went on Metoprolol, which
is a commonly used beta blocker,

00:48:54.080 --> 00:48:57.100
which she went on initially
for her ventricular tachycardia

00:48:57.100 --> 00:48:57.744
up here.

00:48:57.744 --> 00:48:59.410
So you can see this
is what she's doing.

00:48:59.410 --> 00:49:01.840
She comes in to see me
here at a BMI of 52.

00:49:01.840 --> 00:49:03.310
Remember, that is
severe obesity--

00:49:03.310 --> 00:49:05.200
BMIs of greater than 40.

00:49:05.200 --> 00:49:09.520
She does have a drop
here to BMI of 26.5.

00:49:09.520 --> 00:49:11.680
So what do we think happened
for this individual?

00:49:11.680 --> 00:49:14.020
Also, notice how her brain
was defending that set point

00:49:14.020 --> 00:49:16.930
kind of in this range of
severe obesity with some ups

00:49:16.930 --> 00:49:22.270
and downs, but never down here,
or never significantly up here.

00:49:22.270 --> 00:49:24.980
So initially, I did behavioral.

00:49:24.980 --> 00:49:26.950
So I figure I'll always
start with behavioral.

00:49:26.950 --> 00:49:29.200
She had a significant drop.

00:49:29.200 --> 00:49:34.174
And then subsequently,
I did surgery for her.

00:49:34.174 --> 00:49:35.590
And so you can see
that we've been

00:49:35.590 --> 00:49:38.110
able to drive her into a
completely different set

00:49:38.110 --> 00:49:40.040
point for her weight.

00:49:40.040 --> 00:49:41.560
Finally, we have a
36-year-old woman

00:49:41.560 --> 00:49:45.220
coming in with hypothyroidism,
dysthymia, meaning low mood,

00:49:45.220 --> 00:49:48.040
allergic rhinitis, chronic
back pain, migraine headaches.

00:49:48.040 --> 00:49:50.170
Has a pretty virtuous diet here.

00:49:50.170 --> 00:49:52.061
Cardio at the gym
five days per week.

00:49:52.061 --> 00:49:53.560
She's on the
elliptical for an hour.

00:49:53.560 --> 00:49:55.300
She walks at lunchtime
for 45 minutes.

00:49:55.300 --> 00:49:58.300
She strength trains three
times per week for one hour.

00:49:58.300 --> 00:50:01.660
Her trainer sends in
the information to me

00:50:01.660 --> 00:50:05.020
on a weekly basis during the
time I was taking care for.

00:50:05.020 --> 00:50:07.600
Sleeps six to seven hours
a night of restful sleep.

00:50:07.600 --> 00:50:09.850
Comes in at a BMI of 36.

00:50:09.850 --> 00:50:12.880
You guys will remember that
class 2 or moderate obesity.

00:50:12.880 --> 00:50:16.210
She does drop here
to this BMI of 29.5.

00:50:16.210 --> 00:50:18.880
So she comes out of obesity
right into what is considered

00:50:18.880 --> 00:50:20.829
overweight category.

00:50:20.829 --> 00:50:22.120
That was with the use of drugs.

00:50:22.120 --> 00:50:25.280
But notice she comes back
within a four month period.

00:50:25.280 --> 00:50:27.380
She comes back with BMI of 36.

00:50:27.380 --> 00:50:31.120
So what happened to
this lovely individual?

00:50:31.120 --> 00:50:34.434
Why does she come back?

00:50:34.434 --> 00:50:35.850
She stopped taking
the medication.

00:50:35.850 --> 00:50:37.790
Why, as a 36-year-old
woman, did she

00:50:37.790 --> 00:50:40.865
stop taking these medications.

00:50:40.865 --> 00:50:41.990
She wanted to get pregnant.

00:50:41.990 --> 00:50:42.590
Absolutely.

00:50:42.590 --> 00:50:44.780
So for all of my women
of childbearing age

00:50:44.780 --> 00:50:47.384
that went to go to
these meds, I tell them,

00:50:47.384 --> 00:50:49.550
I have to stop these because
they're contraindicated

00:50:49.550 --> 00:50:51.080
during use of pregnancy.

00:50:51.080 --> 00:50:54.000
And it took us two years
for her to lose the weight.

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:56.270
Four months for her to
gain the weight back.

00:50:56.270 --> 00:50:59.240
So it shows you that if
I stop these medications,

00:50:59.240 --> 00:51:00.974
that is quite an issue.

00:51:00.974 --> 00:51:02.640
I promise in two
minutes, we'll be done.

00:51:02.640 --> 00:51:05.760
The costs of obesity around
the world-- pretty steep.

00:51:05.760 --> 00:51:07.430
And this is taken
from 2014 data,

00:51:07.430 --> 00:51:09.260
so the numbers are
probably even steeper.

00:51:09.260 --> 00:51:12.650
There's is no good study that
supports the new numbers.

00:51:12.650 --> 00:51:15.830
You can see the United States
down here to $147 billion.

00:51:15.830 --> 00:51:18.890
Some estimates are
upwards of $350 billion

00:51:18.890 --> 00:51:20.420
here in the United States.

00:51:20.420 --> 00:51:24.620
When we look at it from its
impact on the global GDP,

00:51:24.620 --> 00:51:27.780
$2.1 trillion for smoking,
$2.1 for armed violence,

00:51:27.780 --> 00:51:28.790
war on terrorism.

00:51:28.790 --> 00:51:32.870
$2 trillion for obesity.
$1.4 trillion for alcoholism.

00:51:32.870 --> 00:51:35.400
So this is a big policy issue.

00:51:35.400 --> 00:51:37.370
So it's the big
policy issue, and we

00:51:37.370 --> 00:51:38.540
should have some targets.

00:51:38.540 --> 00:51:40.970
Let's look at what we're doing
here in the United States.

00:51:40.970 --> 00:51:42.770
We have some obesity
targets, but do we

00:51:42.770 --> 00:51:44.270
have any national
obesity policy?

00:51:44.270 --> 00:51:45.075
No.

00:51:45.075 --> 00:51:47.490
State long policy, it depends.

00:51:47.490 --> 00:51:49.612
Guidance-- so surgery
and drugs-- yes.

00:51:49.612 --> 00:51:52.070
So why is it that we haven't
looked at all of these things?

00:51:52.070 --> 00:51:53.944
I can tell you that
right now before Congress

00:51:53.944 --> 00:51:56.270
is the Treat and Reduce
Obesity Act, which

00:51:56.270 --> 00:51:58.640
has gone now before
Congress for the third time.

00:51:58.640 --> 00:52:02.480
I've been on Capitol Hill
way too often lately.

00:52:02.480 --> 00:52:05.240
And it's really to support
the treatment of obesity

00:52:05.240 --> 00:52:07.160
for those individuals
that have obesity.

00:52:07.160 --> 00:52:09.170
It does have bipartisan
support, but it just

00:52:09.170 --> 00:52:11.510
has not risen to the
level of importance

00:52:11.510 --> 00:52:13.880
such that it ever gets passed.

00:52:13.880 --> 00:52:15.200
So what's the summary?

00:52:15.200 --> 00:52:17.785
Obesity is a
multi-factorial disorder,

00:52:17.785 --> 00:52:19.910
and conventional weight
loss should consist of diet

00:52:19.910 --> 00:52:22.310
and exercise first,
but we may need

00:52:22.310 --> 00:52:24.860
to utilize additional
tools to treat individuals

00:52:24.860 --> 00:52:26.750
that struggle with obesity.

00:52:26.750 --> 00:52:28.880
Pharmacotherapy and/or
bariatric surgery

00:52:28.880 --> 00:52:30.380
should be considered
as an option

00:52:30.380 --> 00:52:32.540
for appropriate patients.

00:52:32.540 --> 00:52:36.800
And that weight bias is
seen as early as infancy.

00:52:36.800 --> 00:52:39.230
Maternal and paternal
anti-fat bias

00:52:39.230 --> 00:52:41.960
does significantly influence
children's behavior,

00:52:41.960 --> 00:52:45.320
and that can have huge
implications for individuals.

00:52:45.320 --> 00:52:47.360
We know that weight stigma
has a negative impact

00:52:47.360 --> 00:52:50.300
on the health and psychological
health of patients

00:52:50.300 --> 00:52:52.292
who struggle with obesity.

00:52:52.292 --> 00:52:53.750
Obesity is a chronic
disease, which

00:52:53.750 --> 00:52:57.740
requires lifelong
treatment and management.

00:52:57.740 --> 00:53:00.009
I'd like to thank you
so much for your time.

00:53:00.009 --> 00:53:02.300
And I don't know if I have
time to entertain questions,

00:53:02.300 --> 00:53:04.520
but I'm available to
entertain questions.

00:53:04.520 --> 00:53:05.797
So thank you so much.

00:53:05.797 --> 00:53:07.665
[APPLAUSE]

00:53:11.870 --> 00:53:13.760
I think they're going
to bring up mics.

00:53:13.760 --> 00:53:15.980
I can hear very
well, so I'm going

00:53:15.980 --> 00:53:17.510
to repeat back the question.

00:53:17.510 --> 00:53:19.578
You have a question.

00:53:19.578 --> 00:53:23.952
- What do you know about the
[INAUDIBLE] to talking about

00:53:23.952 --> 00:53:28.070
[INAUDIBLE]

00:53:28.070 --> 00:53:28.570
- 80-20.

00:53:28.570 --> 00:53:29.980
Tell me talk about the 80-20.

00:53:29.980 --> 00:53:36.170
- Like the 20% of
factors [INAUDIBLE]..

00:53:36.170 --> 00:53:36.670
- OK.

00:53:36.670 --> 00:53:40.490
So the question was, what
do we know, basically,

00:53:40.490 --> 00:53:44.840
about the contributing factors,
and the relative importance,

00:53:44.840 --> 00:53:47.116
or how they play a role.

00:53:47.116 --> 00:53:49.490
I'm going to say that the only
thing we definitively know

00:53:49.490 --> 00:53:53.450
is that genetics
contributes to 60% to 70%

00:53:53.450 --> 00:53:55.130
of obesity in this country.

00:53:55.130 --> 00:53:57.800
And that's been well
studied and well regulated.

00:53:57.800 --> 00:53:59.720
No one has done a really
great study looking

00:53:59.720 --> 00:54:01.320
at promoting medications.

00:54:01.320 --> 00:54:04.140
We do know sleep, quality of
diet, and all of those things

00:54:04.140 --> 00:54:04.640
play a role.

00:54:04.640 --> 00:54:06.424
But it's hard to say.

00:54:06.424 --> 00:54:08.090
And I think that one
of the things we do

00:54:08.090 --> 00:54:09.620
is we try to generalize it.

00:54:09.620 --> 00:54:12.020
And it's important for
me, as an individual,

00:54:12.020 --> 00:54:14.540
when I'm working with
patients, to personalize it.

00:54:14.540 --> 00:54:16.580
Because one
individual may walk in

00:54:16.580 --> 00:54:19.370
and you can see that they
respond very differently.

00:54:19.370 --> 00:54:21.620
And so I have to listen to
the nuances of what they're

00:54:21.620 --> 00:54:23.390
telling me when I'm treating.

00:54:23.390 --> 00:54:26.260
Now in terms of that
prevention side of things,

00:54:26.260 --> 00:54:27.890
I think there's some
universal themes

00:54:27.890 --> 00:54:29.329
with regard to prevention.

00:54:29.329 --> 00:54:31.370
You know, we can't change
our mom and dad, right?

00:54:31.370 --> 00:54:33.710
So if your mom and
dad have obesity,

00:54:33.710 --> 00:54:36.780
the likelihood you have
obesity is relatively high.

00:54:36.780 --> 00:54:38.630
You can't pick the parents.

00:54:38.630 --> 00:54:41.370
But we can modify
maybe the mom going in

00:54:41.370 --> 00:54:44.450
before she has a child to
modify her as much as we can.

00:54:44.450 --> 00:54:46.280
Recognizing that we
can't fix the genetics

00:54:46.280 --> 00:54:48.190
or the epigenetic
piece of things.

00:54:48.190 --> 00:54:49.820
And so I think about that--

00:54:49.820 --> 00:54:52.760
those broad statements are more
applicable to the prevention

00:54:52.760 --> 00:54:54.599
side of things as
opposed to what

00:54:54.599 --> 00:54:57.140
I do for the individual patient
that's sitting in front of me

00:54:57.140 --> 00:54:58.490
in that chair in the office.

00:54:58.490 --> 00:55:01.050
Hopefully, that explains
kind of some of the things.

00:55:01.050 --> 00:55:01.550
Yes?

00:55:01.550 --> 00:55:02.210
- Hi, thanks.

00:55:02.210 --> 00:55:03.200
- Hi, how are you?

00:55:03.200 --> 00:55:04.610
- Good, thank you.

00:55:04.610 --> 00:55:05.649
Two questions.

00:55:05.649 --> 00:55:07.190
- We'll start with
one, and then I'll

00:55:07.190 --> 00:55:08.780
do the second one, because
my brain may not remember.

00:55:08.780 --> 00:55:09.730
- OK.

00:55:09.730 --> 00:55:14.600
Behavioral methods-- what
do they usually involve?

00:55:14.600 --> 00:55:16.499
Just dietary change?

00:55:16.499 --> 00:55:18.290
- OK, so she asked
about behavioral methods

00:55:18.290 --> 00:55:19.430
for weight regulation.

00:55:19.430 --> 00:55:20.420
It depends.

00:55:20.420 --> 00:55:22.400
I think of behavior
as encompassing

00:55:22.400 --> 00:55:25.070
not only the diet
quality, but also,

00:55:25.070 --> 00:55:27.200
looking at the quality
and consistency

00:55:27.200 --> 00:55:28.430
of physical activity, right?

00:55:28.430 --> 00:55:31.250
So we need at least 150
minutes of moderate intensity

00:55:31.250 --> 00:55:34.904
physical activity per week
based upon the 2008 guidelines

00:55:34.904 --> 00:55:37.070
from the US department of
Health and Human Services.

00:55:37.070 --> 00:55:38.610
I can tell you that by
the end of this year,

00:55:38.610 --> 00:55:40.400
there are new guidelines
that will likely come out,

00:55:40.400 --> 00:55:42.020
which will be much
more aggressive.

00:55:42.020 --> 00:55:43.250
Because what we've
seen-- and I don't

00:55:43.250 --> 00:55:44.750
know if you guys have seen
the study that came out

00:55:44.750 --> 00:55:47.450
last week-- that activity
levels have actually increased

00:55:47.450 --> 00:55:48.980
dramatically over
the last 10 years

00:55:48.980 --> 00:55:50.870
amongst the US population.

00:55:50.870 --> 00:55:52.680
But the obesity
rates also increase.

00:55:52.680 --> 00:55:54.920
So it goes to show you
that physical activity is

00:55:54.920 --> 00:55:57.160
one thing that can
potentially help

00:55:57.160 --> 00:56:00.920
quell the obesity epidemic, but
it is not the end all, be all.

00:56:00.920 --> 00:56:03.100
When we're looking at
behavior, many of our patients

00:56:03.100 --> 00:56:05.087
do struggle with
psychological contributors

00:56:05.087 --> 00:56:06.420
to weight and weight regulation.

00:56:06.420 --> 00:56:08.855
So they may need intensive
work with psychologists

00:56:08.855 --> 00:56:11.720
or psychiatrists to
delve into issues

00:56:11.720 --> 00:56:15.650
that are leading to maladaptive
behaviors like we talked about.

00:56:15.650 --> 00:56:17.900
So that may be part of that.

